1) JVM Architecture
👉 The Java Virtual Machine (JVM) executes Java bytecode. It sits between compiled .class files and the OS.
High-level Flow

Java Source (.java)  →  Compiler (javac)  →  Bytecode (.class)  →  JVM  →  Machine Code



Main Components
1. Class Loader Subsystem
    * Loads .class files into memory.
    * Phases: Loading → Linking → Initialization.
    * Delegation model (Bootstrap → Extension → Application classloader).
2. Runtime Data Areas
    * Method Area: Stores class metadata, static variables.
    * Heap: Stores objects (shared memory).
    * Stack: Each thread has its own stack → stores method frames, local variables.
    * PC Register: Stores address of current instruction for each thread.
    * Native Method Stack: For methods written in C/C++ (JNI).
3. Execution Engine
    * Interpreter: Reads bytecode line by line (slow).
    * JIT Compiler: Compiles hot code into native code for speed.
    * Garbage Collector (GC): Manages memory (removes unused objects).
4. Native Libraries
    * JNI interface → connects JVM with OS-dependent native libraries.

Real-Time Example to Impress Interviewer
👉 Suppose you run a Spring Boot microservice.
1. JVM loads classes like EmployeeService.class via Class Loader.
2. Heap stores all Employee objects created when requests come.
3. Stack stores request thread variables (like requestId).
4. JIT optimizes repeated service methods.
5. GC removes old Employee objects after request completes.

5. Quick Summary (Good to tell interviewer)
👉 JVM Architecture = Class Loader + Runtime Data Areas + Execution Engine.
* Class Loader → loads classes.
* Memory Areas → stores code, objects, variables.
* Execution Engine → runs bytecode (Interpreter + JIT + GC).



